			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">As was mentioned already, you absolutely do not and should not need to process the APU stuff at 1.7 MHz. What I do is just determine and keep track of how often each channel's sample gets updated (in terms of CPU ticks) and after every CPU instruction emulated, I check if it's time to do so yet. Likewise, I determine how many samples to create per second by taking the number of CPU ticks per second and dividing by the sample rate. Whenever it's time to create a new sample and put it in the output buffer, all I have to do is mix the sample value from all channels into one sample. That's all.<br /><br />The APU emulation takes nowhere near the CPU power of PPU emulaion. In fact, if you did only the APU stuff and ignored all graphics stuff, it would probably be fast enough to generate the audio full speed on a 386, or possibly even a high-end 286!</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
							</td>
						</tr>
						</table>
					</td>
				</tr>
				</table>
			</td>
		</tr>

